==============================================================================
QUESTION 1: WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE SLICE ISOLATION
Does a prior NO_OVERWRITE write to region [a,b) remain valid at the Draw that
reads it, even after a second NO_OVERWRITE write to non-overlapping region [c,d)?
==============================================================================

ANSWER: YES — guaranteed, provided the application upholds its half of the contract.

CITATION [S1] — D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE contract (verbatim):

  "D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE signifies that the application promises not to
   write to data that the input assembler (IA) stage is using. In exchange, the
   GPU allows the application to write to other parts of the same buffer. The
   application must ensure that it does not write over any data in use by the
   IA stage."

  "For example, consider the buffer illustrated in the following diagram. If a
   Draw call has been issued that uses vertices 4-6, then an application that
   calls Map on this buffer must ensure that it does not write to the vertices
   that the Draw call will access during rendering."

CITATION [S2] — How to Use Dynamic Resources (verbatim):

  "D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE indicates that the app will not overwrite data
   already in use in the dynamic buffer. The Map call will return a pointer to
   the old data, which will allow the app to add new data in unused regions of
   the vertex or index buffer. The app must not modify vertices or indices that
   are used in a draw operation as they might still be in use by the GPU."

INTERPRETATION:
- WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE does NOT rename the buffer or allocate new backing memory.
  It returns a pointer into the SAME physical memory as the prior Map calls.
  [S7] confirms: the DXVK fast path for NO_OVERWRITE "returns the existing
  mapped pointer directly via GetMapPtr()", trusting the application's guarantee.
- The GPU "allows" writes to non-in-use regions precisely because the application
  has promised not to touch in-use regions. Both [a,b) and [c,d) are visible in
  the same memory at the same GPU address. A DrawIndexed that reads [a,b), issued
  in API submission order AFTER both writes and after Unmap on each, will read
  the correct first write's data. Region [c,d) is at a different offset and does
  not disturb [a,b).
- The runtime provides NO additional isolation between NO_OVERWRITE slices beyond
  the application's own promise. If the application were to accidentally write
  into [a,b) during the second NO_OVERWRITE Map, the GPU could read corrupted
  data with no API-level error.

CONCLUSION FOR Q1: Region [a,b) is guaranteed to contain the first write's data
at the time of the Draw, as long as:
  (a) The application did not write into [a,b) during any subsequent NO_OVERWRITE
      Map (the application promise).
  (b) No WRITE_DISCARD occurred between the write to [a,b) and the Draw that
      reads it (see Q2 — DISCARD invalidates the entire buffer).
  (c) The Draw is issued on the same immediate context in submission order after
      Unmap (see Q4 — no additional sync needed on immediate context).

==============================================================================
QUESTION 2: WRITE_DISCARD — WHOLE BUFFER OR MAPPED REGION ONLY?
==============================================================================

ANSWER: WRITE_DISCARD invalidates / discards the ENTIRE buffer, not just the
mapped region or the byte range the application happens to write into.

CITATION [S2] — How to Use Dynamic Resources (verbatim, emphasis in source):

  "Note: When you map a buffer with D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD, the runtime always
   discards the entire buffer. You can't preserve info in unmapped areas of the
   buffer by specifying a nonzero offset or limited size field."

CITATION [S1] — D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD definition (verbatim):

  "Resource is mapped for writing; the previous contents of the resource will
   be undefined. The resource must have been created with write access and
   dynamic usage."

CITATION [S2] — Rename / new backing memory semantics (verbatim):

  "D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD indicates that the app doesn't need to keep the old
   vertex or index data in the buffer. If the GPU is still using the buffer when
   you call Map with D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD, the runtime returns a pointer to a
   new region of memory instead of the old buffer data. This allows the GPU to
   continue using the old data while the app places data in the new buffer. No
   additional memory management is required in the app; the old buffer is reused
   or destroyed automatically when the GPU is finished with it."

CITATION [S5] / [S11] — D3D12 removal explains the D3D11 model (paraphrase):

  "In D3D11, applications were able to map dynamic resources with a DISCARD flag.
   Because the particular memory allocation currently linked to the resource is
   not exposed at the API level (only the abstract 'resource'), drivers had to
   perform this tracking behind-the-scenes." (D3D12 removes this driver-managed
   rename because it is incompatible with multi-threaded recording.)

CITATION [S7/S8] — DXVK implementation confirms rename-the-whole-buffer:

  "Allocate a new backing slice for the buffer and set it as the 'new' mapped
   slice." DXVK emits a command to "invalidate the old buffer with this new
   slice" — the invalidation covers the entire resource object, not a sub-range.

CRITICAL IMPLICATION FOR THE RING SCENARIO:

If, at any point during a frame, you call Map(WRITE_DISCARD) on the same buffer
you have been using as a ring:

  1. The runtime/driver switches the buffer object to a completely new backing
     memory allocation. The CPU receives a pointer to this new allocation.
  2. Any data previously written into the OLD allocation (all prior NO_OVERWRITE
     slices) is no longer accessible through this buffer object for draws NOT YET
     ISSUED. Prior-written slices are gone from the application's perspective.
  3. HOWEVER, draws that were ALREADY ISSUED (submitted to the immediate context
     command queue) BEFORE the DISCARD call will still read from the old backing
     memory correctly — the driver retains the old allocation until GPU execution
     of those prior draws completes. This is the "allows the GPU to continue
     using the old data" guarantee.
  4. Draws issued AFTER the DISCARD call will read from the new (discarded/blank)
     backing memory. If the application has not re-written those vertex regions
     into the new allocation, the GPU will read undefined/garbage data.

BOTTOM LINE: DISCARD is a whole-buffer operation. It is NOT safe to DISCARD
mid-ring and expect old NO_OVERWRITE slices to remain valid for draws that have
not yet been issued. All draws for previously-written slices MUST be issued
before any DISCARD on the same buffer.

==============================================================================
QUESTION 3: CAN A WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE REGION BE CLOBBERED BY DRIVER/WDDM
ON A SINGLE IMMEDIATE CONTEXT?
==============================================================================

ANSWER: No documented driver/WDDM mechanism causes clobbering of a correctly-
used NO_OVERWRITE region on a single immediate context. The contract is
unidirectional: the application promises not to overwrite GPU-in-use regions;
in exchange the driver promises not to interfere with application writes to
other regions.

CITATION [S1] — Remarks on NO_OVERWRITE (verbatim):

  "However, ensuring this can be difficult, because the GPU is often many frames
   behind the CPU in terms of which frame it is currently processing. Keeping
   track of which sections of a resource are being used because of calls made 2
   to 5 frames ago is difficult and error-prone. Because of this, it is
   recommended that applications only write to the uninitialized portions of a
   resource when using D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE."

This passage documents the PRACTICAL HAZARD: the application may incorrectly
believe a region is free when the GPU is still using it — but this is entirely
on the application. The driver does not clobber NO_OVERWRITE regions; only the
application can break this contract.

DOCUMENTED RISK — "reads before CPU write visible": NOT a risk on a single
immediate context. On the immediate context, Map/Unmap establishes happens-before
with subsequent Draw calls in API submission order (see Q4). The CPU write IS
visible to the GPU by the time the Draw executes, because the immediate context
serializes operations.

DOCUMENTED RISK — Write-combine memory: [S3] warns:

  "When you pass D3D11_MAP_WRITE, D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD, or
   D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE to the MapType parameter, you must ensure that
   your app does not read the subresource data to which the pData member of
   D3D11_MAPPED_SUBRESOURCE points because doing so can cause a significant
   performance penalty. The memory region to which pData points can be allocated
   with PAGE_WRITECOMBINE..."

  Additionally: "Even the following C++ code can read from memory and trigger the
   performance penalty because the code can expand to x86 AND DWORD PTR:
   *((int*)MappedResource.pData) = 0;"

  This is a CPU PERFORMANCE concern (WC memory is slow to read), NOT a GPU
  visibility or correctness hazard. Use non-temporal stores or memcpy for fills.

CONCLUSION FOR Q3: No documented driver/WDDM behavior clobbers a correctly-used
NO_OVERWRITE region. The only hazard is the application violating its own promise
(writing into GPU-in-use bytes), or using WRITE_DISCARD on the same buffer (which
renames the backing memory for all future draws, leaving prior-write slices on the
old backing — safe for already-issued draws, unsafe for draws not yet issued).

==============================================================================
QUESTION 4: MAP/UNMAP → DRAW ORDERING ON A SINGLE IMMEDIATE CONTEXT
==============================================================================

ANSWER: API submission order IS the ordering guarantee. No manual synchronization
(fences, barriers, events) is needed. Unmap completing before the subsequent Draw
call in the same thread on the same immediate context is sufficient.

CITATION [S4] — Immediate context design (verbatim):

  "Immediate rendering refers to calling rendering APIs or commands from a device,
   which queues the commands in a buffer for execution on the GPU."

  The immediate context is strictly single-threaded. There is no documented
  mechanism by which a Draw issued later in the same thread could begin GPU
  execution before a Map/Unmap issued earlier in that thread has made the CPU
  writes available. The driver/runtime queues commands in order.

CITATION [S2] — Synchronization via WRITE_DISCARD for static-pattern use (verbatim):

  "When you map a buffer with D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD or no map values, you are
   always guaranteed that the vertices are synchronized properly with the GPU."

  While this sentence focuses on DISCARD, it confirms the general principle that
  Map/Unmap provides a defined synchronization point with the GPU work queue.

CITATION [S3] — No mention of any fence or barrier requirement between Map/Unmap
and Draw on an immediate context. The API implicitly provides serialization.

DXVK [S7] — sequence-number tracking across draw submissions is used for resource
reuse decisions (to know when old backing memory is GPU-idle), NOT to impose
barriers between Map and Draw on the same context. The immediate context's command
stream IS the ordering mechanism.

NOTE on D3D11_MAP_FLAG_DO_NOT_WAIT: This flag can cause Map to return
DXGI_ERROR_WAS_STILL_DRAWING if the GPU is not yet done with the resource. In
normal (non-NO_OVERWRITE) usage this would be a stall risk. For a correctly-used
ring (NO_OVERWRITE always, DISCARD only on wrap), this flag is unnecessary — the
application guarantees it is not writing to GPU-in-use regions, so there is no
GPU stall.

CONCLUSION FOR Q4: On a single immediate context, submission order is the only
synchronization needed. Calling Map(NO_OVERWRITE) → write → Unmap → then later
DrawIndexed (all in the same thread on the immediate context) guarantees the GPU
sees the CPU-written data when the draw executes. No additional manual sync is
required.

==============================================================================
QUESTION 5: KNOWN CORRECTNESS PITFALLS OF THE ONE-BUFFER RING PATTERN
==============================================================================

The canonical pattern is: DISCARD on first use per frame (or on wrap), then
NO_OVERWRITE for subsequent appends within the frame. Several pitfalls exist.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PITFALL A (CRITICAL): WRITE_DISCARD WHILE PENDING DRAWS STILL NEED PRIOR SLICES
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

This is the most dangerous pitfall and directly answers the "deferred draw" sub-
question.

Scenario: You write slice [a,b) with NO_OVERWRITE, then write slice [c,d) with
NO_OVERWRITE, then call Map(WRITE_DISCARD) before issuing the DrawIndexed for
[a,b).

Result: DISCARD renames the entire buffer to new backing memory (as shown in Q2).
The draw for [a,b) is now issued against the new (empty/undefined) backing memory.
The data written to [a,b) lives on the OLD backing memory that the driver may
release as soon as it knows no draws reference it. If no draws were issued against
the OLD backing before the DISCARD, the driver may recycle it immediately. The
draw then reads garbage.

CITATION [S2] (verbatim):
  "Note: When you map a buffer with D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD, the runtime always
   discards the entire buffer. You can't preserve info in unmapped areas of the
   buffer by specifying a nonzero offset or limited size field."

MICROSOFT REFERENCE FIX — DirectXTK PrimitiveBatch [S6] always issues the draw
(FlushBatch()) BEFORE calling DISCARD (verbatim from implementation analysis):

  "The implementation calls FlushBatch() *before* resetting positions...
   'if (... wrapVertexBuffer) { FlushBatch(); }' — This ensures any pending draw
   calls execute using the current buffer contents *before* a DISCARD invalidates
   that data."

RULE: Every slice written with NO_OVERWRITE must have its DrawIndexed issued
(submitted to the immediate context) BEFORE any subsequent Map(WRITE_DISCARD) on
the same buffer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PITFALL B: WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE ON A REGION THE GPU IS STILL READING
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CITATION [S1] (verbatim):
  "The GPU is often many frames behind the CPU in terms of which frame it is
   currently processing. Keeping track of which sections of a resource are being
   used because of calls made 2 to 5 frames ago is difficult and error-prone."

In a multi-frame ring (buffer reused across frames), after completing one full
revolution, the CPU write head re-enters bytes that the GPU may still be executing
against from a prior frame. Writing there with NO_OVERWRITE violates the
application promise and the GPU reads partially-written or wrong data —
silently, with no API error.

FIX: The safe half-measure from Microsoft is to only ever write into "uninitialized
portions" of the ring [S1]. The full-correct approach requires either:
  (a) Ensuring the ring is large enough that the CPU never catches the GPU
      (N frames of CPU latency * worst-case per-frame byte consumption, rounded
      up to a safe multiple), OR
  (b) Using D3D11_QUERY_EVENT after the last draw of a frame to confirm GPU idle
      before re-entering old regions [S2]:
        "Issue a query of type D3D11_QUERY_EVENT after the last draw call that
         uses the vertices. The vertices are no longer in use when
         ID3D11DeviceContext::GetData returns S_OK."

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PITFALL C: WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE NOT VALID FOR CONSTANT BUFFERS (D3D11.0)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CITATION [S1] (verbatim):
  "This flag is only valid on vertex and index buffers. The resource must have
   been created with write access. Cannot be used on a resource created with the
   D3D11_BIND_CONSTANT_BUFFER flag."

  "The Direct3D 11.1 runtime, which is available starting with Windows 8, enables
   mapping dynamic constant buffers and shader resource views (SRVs) of dynamic
   buffers with D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE."

The ring pattern using NO_OVERWRITE for a VERTEX buffer (as in the SWG client
DynamicVertexBufferData usage) is valid on D3D11.0+. Attempting the same pattern
for a constant buffer requires 11.1 + CheckFeatureSupport confirmation of
MapNoOverwriteOnDynamicConstantBuffer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PITFALL D: PAGE_WRITECOMBINE PENALTY FROM READS THROUGH THE MAP POINTER
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CITATION [S3] (verbatim):
  "The memory region to which pData points can be allocated with PAGE_WRITECOMBINE,
   and your app must honor all restrictions that are associated with such memory."

WC memory is write-only from the CPU perspective (reads are slow and may be
reordered or go to uncached paths). Using a non-streaming memcpy or any C++
construct that reads-back the destination (e.g., compound assignment operators
expanding to AND DWORD PTR) incurs severe performance penalties. This is a
performance issue, not a correctness issue, but it manifests as unexplained CPU-
side stalls in the Map-write loop.

FIX: Use memcpy (which compilers typically optimize with non-temporal stores for
WC targets) or _mm_stream_* intrinsics. Avoid any read-modify-write through the
pData pointer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PITFALL E: ASSUMING DISCARD ONLY AFFECTS THE BYTES YOU WRITE
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

A common misconception is that WRITE_DISCARD with a small written region only
invalidates the written bytes, leaving other bytes at their old values. This is
explicitly false — the ENTIRE buffer is renamed [S2]. Applications that skip the
first-frame DISCARD and jump straight to NO_OVERWRITE may read driver-undefined
values in the pre-write bytes if the driver returned new-allocation memory.

FIX: Always begin a frame's ring usage with exactly one WRITE_DISCARD (at position
0), then switch to NO_OVERWRITE for all subsequent writes that frame. [S2]

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PITFALL F: DEFERRED CONTEXT RESTRICTION
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CITATION [S3/S4] (verbatim):
  "If you call Map on a deferred context, you can only pass D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD,
   D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE, or both to the MapType parameter. Other D3D11_MAP-
   typed values are not supported for a deferred context."

  "The Map method is only supported in a deferred context for dynamic resources
   (D3D11_USAGE_DYNAMIC) where the first call within the command list is
   D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD. D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE is supported on
   subsequent calls if available for the given type of resource."

The ring pattern is supported on deferred contexts, but the FIRST Map in each
command list MUST be WRITE_DISCARD. A deferred context cannot begin with
NO_OVERWRITE. This is not a concern for immediate-context use.

==============================================================================
SUMMARY TABLE
==============================================================================

Question | Key Finding
---------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Q1       | YES: [a,b) data is preserved at Draw time. NO_OVERWRITE does not rename
         | the buffer; same physical memory throughout. Non-overlapping [c,d) write
         | is harmless to [a,b). Application promise is the sole guard.
---------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Q2       | WRITE_DISCARD renames THE WHOLE BUFFER unconditionally (not just the
         | mapped region). Previous contents of all slices become undefined for
         | draws not yet issued. Draws already issued before DISCARD are safe (driver
         | retains old backing until GPU finishes). No way to preserve prior-slice
         | data through a DISCARD.
---------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Q3       | No driver/WDDM mechanism clobbers a correct NO_OVERWRITE region.
         | Only hazards: (a) app writes into GPU-in-use bytes (app bug, silent), or
         | (b) WRITE_DISCARD called before pending draws (see Q2/Q5-A). WC memory
         | read penalty is a perf issue, not correctness.
---------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Q4       | Immediate context submission order IS the synchronization. Map → write →
         | Unmap → Draw in same thread = CPU data visible at GPU draw time.
         | No manual fence/barrier needed.
---------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Q5       | FATAL: Issuing WRITE_DISCARD before all pending-slice draws clobbers
         | unissued draws (they see new empty backing). Always FlushBatch()/issue
         | all draws before DISCARD. Also: multi-frame ring overflow writes GPU-
         | in-use bytes silently; WC read-back penalty; CBV restriction on D3D11.0.

==============================================================================
APPLICATION TO SWG CLIENT Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData
==============================================================================

The SWG client ring pattern (as of koogie-msvc-cpp20-base branch) uses a single
D3D11_USAGE_DYNAMIC vertex buffer as a per-frame ring, with WRITE_DISCARD at the
start of the frame and WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE for per-draw appends. The cape/spike
skinning regression (.planning/research/cape-spike-evidence/) is characterized as
"undefined-memory-zero-on-replay" — consistent with a DISCARD being called while
slices have been written but their draws have not yet been issued (Pitfall A).

Key questions to answer with RenderDoc:
1. Is WRITE_DISCARD called mid-frame before DrawIndexed for prior NO_OVERWRITE
   slices?
2. Does the VB offset passed to IASetVertexBuffers for the Draw point into a
   region that was written BEFORE the most recent DISCARD?
3. Is the VB fence-point (buffer rename) happening inside
   Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData::lock() on the softskin path, and are
   softskin draws deferred until after other draws that trigger a DISCARD wrap?

If the softskin primitives write vertices (via SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive)
then defer their draw until after a DISCARD-triggering wrap, the entire softskin
slice is invalidated. The GPU will draw using zeroed (new-allocation) memory,
which explains both the spike geometry (zero positions = origin collapse) and the
"invisible on replay" characteristic (capture tools re-execute the command stream
against the renamed buffer, not the original one).

